title: For Sale:  NIB: DPMS Oracle 5.56 Flat-Top 60531
postcontent:
DPMS Oracle 5.56 rifle, optics-ready flattop, mfg. # 60531

Large, detailed pics here http://www.BrokeVW.com/DPMS.html 

Seeking $550 cash but open to offers close to that, no trades.
Most places online seem to be sold out of them with prices hovering around $500 before shipping, FFL fee, taxes, etc...

No Ohio Sales Tax collected, no shipping costs (although I can ship it within OH), no FFL or 4473 required (I will request to look at your Ohio DL or CCW though, and can provide mine on request),  cash only, willing to drive a reasonable distance to meet up in a public place.

New In Box: DPMS Panther Arms 'Oracle' rifle, 5.56mm, Flattop (optics ready), Mfg. # 60531 / RFA3-OC

DPMS site link: http://www.dpmsinc.com/556-ORACLE_ep_135-1.html

Caliber:  5.56 NATO / .223 Remington
Weight (lbs): 6.4 lbs
Length: 32.5"/ 36.5
Barrel: 16" Lightweight 4140 Chromemoly                                                               
Upper Receiver:Forged 7075 T6 - A3 Style Flattop
Twist: 1x9
Lower Receiver:Forged 7075 T6
Stock: Pardus, Com. Tube
Fire Control: Standard AR-15
Handguard: Glacier Guard
Pistol Grip: A2 Style
Front/Rear sight: Railed Gas Block / Optics Ready
Flash Hider: A2 Style Birdcage

From the DPMS Site:
"The best value around. Quite possibly our best value yet. This lightweight optics ready carbine features a mil-std A3 upper receiver, lightweight barrel and Pardus stock for user comfort and advanced capability. All of this and plenty more, at a price set for any budget. "
MSRP - $739.00

Included in the box are what looks like a cleaning solution or wipes, manual, chamber flag, gun lock and a 30-rd. Magpul Pmag.

Anyway, I've looked up reviews on this rifle, and I have noticed more than one difference in what I have to sell, and what they review online... with pics to back up what I have found. Any changes I notate below are from DPMS, I haven't touched them other than to get pics of them, so the changes are factory changes.

Reviews online of the DPMS Oracle rifle include the following detracting points:
--Poorly staked gas key screws/bolts
--Non-Staked Castle nuts
--Semi-Auto-cut Bolt Carrier Groups (BCG's)
--No thread-locker on the gas block screws

Obviously concerned, I opened one of my boxes and had a look.... these *absolutely* have properly staked gas key bolts (Allen-type bolts, not YFS brand)... the extension tube/buffer tube castle nut *is* staked (although it could be better staked).... the BCG is indeed a full-auto/M16 style BCG, which is really only important if you wish to run something like the Fostech Echo-II Binary trigger... and there is definitely some thread locker compound on the front gas block screws.

So.... all of the 'bad points' about this rifle in all the online reviews I have seen have been addressed by DPMS with the rifles I have here. 

Some 'bad things' in the reviews which have NOT changed... it still is not a chrome-lined barrel (the BCG is lined) which may or may not bother you-- Chrome=longer life, less accuracy, while non-Chrome=better accuracy, less life.... it does still use a commercial (larger OD) extension/buffer tube for the stock which, again, shouldn't matter unless you want to run a bump-stock or something like that.

Some GOOD things I can say about this rifle... it's very tight. There is *zero* slop between the upper and lower when assembled.... is it very well machined with no nasty machining marks inside the upper, on the BCG, or in the lower. It's a well-made firearm..... the finish is great, it looks like a well-made firearm as it has a nice finish and proper machining.... it's a VERY reasonably priced rifle if you're just getting into the AR-platform market or wish to have a rifle to gift-away or if you need a truck-beater rifle.

I think that is about it... I've covered the good, the bad, mentioned how I want paid and the procedure. If you're keen on making it faster, I *do* have new Slide Fire SSAR-15 MOD stocks (bump stocks) and Fostech Echo-II triggers that we can discuss at the time of sale.

In Pickerington.

Thanks!
